04158nam a22006735i 9780292739734DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212012txu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012016119  a97802927397347 a10.7560/7397272doi  a(DE-B1597)588277  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX00aDG211b.P343 2012 4aDG211 ǂb P343 2012eb 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a870.9/35561 aPagán, Victoria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConspiracy Theory in Latin Literature /cVictoria Pagán. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction From Conspiracy to Conspiracy Theory -- tChapter 1 Conspiracy Theory in action -- tChapter 2 Juvenal and blame -- tChapter 3 Tacitus and punishment -- tChapter 4 Suetonius and suspicion -- tEpilogue: The golden age of Conspiracy Theory -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConspiracy theory as a theoretical framework has emerged only in the last twenty years; commentators are finding it a productive way to explain the actions and thoughts of individuals and societies. In this compelling exploration of Latin literature, Pagán uses conspiracy theory to illuminate the ways that elite Romans invoked conspiracy as they navigated the hierarchies, divisions, and inequalities in their society. By seeming to uncover conspiracy everywhere, Romans could find the need to crush slave revolts, punish rivals with death or exile, dismiss women, denigrate foreigners, or view their emperors with deep suspicion. Expanding on her earlier Conspiracy Narratives in Roman History, Pagán here interprets the works of poets, satirists, historians, and orators—Juvenal, Tacitus, Suetonius, Terence, and Cicero, among others—to reveal how each writer gave voice to fictional or real actors who were engaged in intrigue and motivated by a calculating worldview. Delving into multiple genres, Pagán offers a powerful critique of how conspiracy and conspiracy theory can take hold and thrive when rumor, fear, and secrecy become routine methods of interpreting (and often distorting) past and current events. In Roman society, where knowledge about others was often lacking and stereotypes dominated, conspiracy theory explained how the world worked. The persistence of conspiracy theory, from antiquity to the present day, attests to its potency as a mechanism for confronting the frailties of the human condition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConspiracy in literature. 0aConspiracy theorieszRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh1 aFenster, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFenster, Mark.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73972740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292739734423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292739734/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK